JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand strengthened on Friday ahead of a second ratings decision in as many days, helped by a dollar sunk by a disappointing jobs report that dimmed bets of a US rate hike in the second half of the year.Stocks were up slightly.At 1530 GMT the rand had gained 0.43% to 12.8150 per dollar, extending a rally in the previous session kicked off by Fitch&#8217;s decision to keep its credit rating for the country unchanged at BB-.The greenback, measured against a basket of major currencies, slumped to a 7-month low after data showed the US economy created fewer jobs than expected last month.Fitch downgraded South Africa to subinvestment on both foreign and local currency debt in April after a cabinet reshuffle that saw respected finance minister Pravin Gordhan dismissed.S&amp;P Global Ratings, also in April, cut only foreign currency debt to junk, with traders expecting the agency to also affirm its ratings, although there lingered a risk to the local debt rating, which remains investment grade. S&amp;P was due to publish its follow-up rating decision later on Friday.Read: S&amp;P affirms SA s BB+ rating, negative outlookBonds were also firmer, with the yield on the benchmark bond due in 2026 cutting 11 basis points to 8.43%, a two-month low.On the bourse, the benchmark Top-40 index was up 0.1% at 46 522 points, while the broader All-share index also closed 0.1% in the black on 52 889 points.Barclays Africa Group rose 3.8% to R149, extending its gains into a second day after parent Barclays plc on Thursday found strong demand from investors for a large chunk of its stake in the bank.Clothing and homeware retailer Mr Price was the biggest gainer among the blue-chips as HSBC raised its assessment of the company to &#8220;buy&#8221;, from &#8220;hold&#8221;.Shares in Mr Price, which earlier this week kept its full-year dividend unchanged despite a drop in profit, rallied 5% to R157. 